<div class="section">
  <h3>How it works</h3>
  <p>Passwordlet is a JavaScript bookmarklet that logs you in with a single click. Your passwords are <a href="http://www.ruby-doc.org/stdlib-1.9.3/libdoc/openssl/rdoc/OpenSSL/Cipher.html">securely encrypted</a> in <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Advanced_Encryption_Standard">AES</a> and they are only used to obtain cookies behind the scenes.</p>
  <br />
  <div class="how-it-works">
    <div class="step-1"><p><b>Step 1.</b> Register your domain and account to Passwordlet</p></div>
    <div class="step-2"><p><b>Step 2.</b> Go to the domain and click Passwordlet from your desktop or mobile browser</p></div>
    <div class="step-3"><p><b>Step 3.</b> Now you're logged in!</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <h3>Behind the scenes</h3>
  <p>When you click the JavaScript bookmarklet, Passwordlet logs in to the domain using a library called <a href="http://mechanize.rubyforge.org/">Mechanize</a>. It then grabs the cookies and sets them to your browser. Once the cookie is set, you're safely logged in without manually having entered your credentials. Read my <a href="">blog post</a> to learn more about technical challanges that I encountered during the implementation.</p>
  
  <div class="behind-the-scenes">
